description:
Compile and execute C# code in the Unity Editor.
The code runs on the Editor's main thread, so it can safely call any Unity API (UnityEngine, UnityEditor, etc.).

The code is placed inside the body of `public static async Task<object> ExecuteAsync(..., ExecuteCodeContext ctx, CancellationToken cancellationToken)`. Single-frame code runs to completion immediately; long editor operations can split work across frames with `await ctx.wait`.

Common usings are pre-included: System, System.IO, System.Text, System.Linq, System.Reflection, System.Threading, System.Threading.Tasks, System.Collections, System.Collections.Generic, UnityEngine, UnityEngine.SceneManagement, UnityEngine.UI, UnityEditor, UnityEditor.SceneManagement, UnityEditor.Animations.

Locus auto-injects further `using` directives for common Unity/package namespaces and uniquely resolved project or package types. If a short type name is ambiguous, compilation fails and the error lists the candidate full type names; only then use a fully qualified name or an explicit top-level `using`.

Returning results to the agent:
- print(obj)       — append obj.ToString() to the result buffer (plain text, one line per call)
- printJson(obj)   — serialize to JSON and append. Uses EditorJsonUtility for UnityEngine.Object (full serialized fields), JsonUtility for plain C# objects. Preferred for structured data.
- clear()          — clear the result buffer
- Expression mode  — if the entire code is a single expression, its value is automatically printed.

Async context API: `await ctx.wait` / `await ctx.WaitFrame()` resumes on a later Editor update; `ctx.WaitFrames(int)`, `ctx.WaitSeconds(float)` and `ctx.WaitUntil(Func<bool>)` wait accordingly. `ctx.Progress(title, info, progress)` reports progress to the Locus tool call panel and returns true only if execution is already cancelled; `ctx.ClearProgress()` clears it; `ctx.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` and `ctx.CancellationToken` handle cancellation. For long loops, process a batch per frame, report progress, then `await ctx.wait`. Unity synchronous calls (SaveScene, AssetDatabase.SaveAssets, asset import) still run synchronously while called.

IMPORTANT:
- Bare `return;` fails to compile — exit early with `return null;` (a trailing `return null;` is auto-appended, so explicit returns are usually unnecessary).
- Debug.Log / Debug.LogWarning / Debug.LogError write only to the Unity Console and are NOT captured in the result — always use print() or printJson().
- Do NOT trigger script recompilation (e.g. CompilationPipeline.RequestScriptCompilation() or importing/modifying .cs files) — the Locus plugin would lose its Unity connection.

Examples:
```
// Batch edit with frame yields
var objects = UnityEngine.Object.FindObjectsOfType<GameObject>();
for (int i = 0; i < objects.Length; i++)
{
    objects[i].name = objects[i].name.Trim();
    if (i % 50 == 0)
    {
        ctx.Progress("Normalize names", $"{i}/{objects.Length}", i / (float)objects.Length);
        await ctx.wait;
    }
}
ctx.ClearProgress();
print($"normalized {objects.Length} objects");
```
```
// Single expression — value is auto-returned
Application.unityVersion
```
